2026-03-21 12:00:15,952 [INFO] __main__: Arguments: {"idea": {"Name": "reviewbench", "Title": "ReviewBench: A Holistic Benchmark for Stress-Testing AI-Assisted Scientific Peer Review", "Short Hypothesis": "Current evaluations of AI review systems are narrow, focusing on surface-level helpfulness or isolated attacks. A comprehensive, multi-dimensional benchmark that jointly evaluates core review quality (faithfulness, coverage), robustness to realistic perturbations (format noise, adversarial injections), and consistency is necessary to reveal failure modes and guide the development of reliable systems. This is the best setting because the peer-review task uniquely combines long-document understanding, critical reasoning, and adversarial real-world conditions; a benchmark must simulate this complexity. Simpler evaluations (e.g., single-metric scoring on clean text) fail to capture the system's true operational reliability.", "Related Work": "1) **AI Review Systems (e.g., Ai-Review)**: Provide the operational framework but lack standardized, multi-faceted evaluation. 2) **Adversarial Attacks on Reviewers (Zhou et al., 2025)**: Demonstrates the severe threat of in-paper prompt injection but evaluates it in isolation. Our benchmark integrates this as one critical stress test among many. 3) **NLP Benchmarks (e.g., BIG-bench, HELM)**: Offer methodologies for holistic evaluation but are not tailored to the scientific review task with its specific document formats and required outputs. 4) **Review Quality Metrics**: Prior work (e.g., on human reviews) defines dimensions like helpfulness and fairness, but not for AI systems under adversarial conditions. Our proposal is a novel synthesis: we construct the first benchmark that unifies evaluation of an AI reviewer's core competency, its robustness to benign and malicious distortions, and its behavioral consistency, providing a single framework for comparative analysis and improvement.", "Abstract": "The deployment of AI systems to assist in peer review necessitates rigorous, standardized evaluation beyond simple helpfulness scores. We introduce ReviewBench, a holistic benchmark designed to stress-test AI-assisted review systems across three pillars: Core Quality, Robustness, and Consistency. For Core Quality, we evaluate factual faithfulness to the source paper and coverage of key contributions/limitations using human-annotated test sets. For Robustness, we introduce a suite of realistic perturbations: (a) Format Noise (simulated OCR errors, LaTeX-to-PDF rendering artifacts), (b) Content Ambiguity (intentionally mismatched figures/tables), and (c) Adversarial Injections (both static and optimized prompt-injection attacks as in Zhou et al., 2025). For Consistency, we measure output variance across multiple runs and minor prompt paraphrasing. We instantiate ReviewBench using the Ai-Review framework on a curated corpus of CS arXiv papers, providing fixed train/validation/test splits. Each system produces structured reviews, which are automatically scored across our metric suite. We conduct a baseline evaluation of several state-of-the-art LLMs/VLMs, revealing surprising vulnerabilities—e.g., high core quality scores can mask catastrophic failure under simple format noise or injection attacks. ReviewBench provides a reproducible testbed for the community, enabling apples-to-apples comparisons and guiding the development of more trustworthy AI reviewers.", "Experiments": "1. **Benchmark Construction**: Curate a dataset of 300 CS arXiv papers (100 each for train/val/test) with LaTeX source and PDFs. For the test set, create human-annotated 'key point' summaries (contributions, limitations). 2. **Perturbation Suite Creation**: For each test paper, generate perturbed versions: (i) **Format Noise**: Apply random character swaps/deletions (simulating OCR), remove random LaTeX formatting commands. (ii) **Ambiguity**: Swap captions between two figures/tables. (iii) **Adversarial**: Inject optimized positive-review prompts (following Zhou et al., 2025) at random locations in the text. 3. **Evaluation Protocol**: Use Ai-Review's prompt template as the standard interface. For each system (e.g., GPT-4, Claude 3, Gemini, Llama 3), run inference on: (A) Clean test papers, (B) Each perturbed version. 4. **Metrics**: **Core Quality**: (a) *Faithfulness*: BERTScore F1 between review statements and source sentences. (b) *Coverage*: ROUGE-L between review and human key point summary. **Robustness**: Relative drop in Faithfulness and Coverage scores for each perturbation type vs. clean. **Adversarial Success Rate**: Percentage of injected papers that receive a maximum score. **Consistency**: Std. dev. of scores across 5 runs with different random seeds; std. dev. of scores when paraphrasing the review instruction. 5. **Analysis**: Report aggregate scores per model and per perturbation. Perform ablation: does providing the PDF to a VLM mitigate format noise vs. text-only LLM? Identify which perturbations cause the largest performance drop.", "Risk Factors and Limitations": "1. **Annotation Cost**: Human annotation of key points is labor-intensive. Mitigation: Use a small but high-quality test set (50-100 papers) and employ expert graduate students. 2. **Generalization**: Benchmarked primarily on CS papers. Findings may not transfer to fields with different norms (e.g., mathematics, humanities). We explicitly note this as a limitation and plan domain extension as future work. 3. **Evolving Attacks**: Adversarial methods will evolve. Our benchmark includes a specific attack (Zhou et al., 2025) but cannot be exhaustive. The framework is designed to be extensible with new perturbation modules. 4. **Metric Limitations**: Automatic metrics like BERTScore are imperfect proxies for true understanding. We validate them against human judgment for a subset. 5. **Computational Cost**: Running multiple models on hundreds of paper variants requires significant compute/API budget. Mitigation: Use a mix of open-source and commercial models, and focus analysis on a representative subset."}}
