2026-03-21 12:00:20,068 [INFO] ai_scientist.tools.semantic_scholar: Response Content: {"total": 18, "offset": 0, "next": 10, "data": [{"paperId": "d02f166a16f9cd635ed60e32d5e6c0e746a78dfc", "title": "Unmasking Deceptive Visuals: Benchmarking Multimodal Large Language Models on Misleading Chart Question Answering", "venue": "Conference on Empirical Methods in Natural Language Processing", "year": 2025, "citationCount": 11, "openAccessPdf": {"url": "", "status": null, "license": null, "disclaimer": "Notice: Paper or abstract available at https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.18172, which is s
2026-03-21 12:01:09,470 [INFO] __main__: Action: FinalizeIdea
2026-03-21 12:01:09,475 [INFO] __main__: Arguments: {"idea": {"Name": "contradiction_review", "Title": "ContraReview: Benchmarking AI Reviewers on Detecting Internal Contradictions in Scientific Papers", "Short Hypothesis": "Current AI review systems are evaluated on faithfulness and coverage but not specifically on their ability to detect and reason about internal contradictions within papers (text-text contradictions, text-figure mismatches, overclaims). A specialized benchmark that systematically injects controlled contradictions into real papers will reveal whether AI reviewers can identify these issues, which is crucial for real peer review quality. This is the best setting because contradiction detection requires deep understanding and cross-referencing across the paper, testing reasoning beyond surface-level faithfulness. Simpler evaluations like BERTScore don't capture this specific critical reasoning skill.", "Related Work": "1) **MMReview (Gao et al., 2025)**: A comprehensive multimodal review benchmark with 13 tasks, but none specifically focused on contradiction detection. Our benchmark is complementary, specializing in this critical aspect. 2) **Misleading ChartQA (Chen et al., 2025)**: Evaluates MLLMs on misleading charts but in isolation, not integrated into full paper review with textual context. 3) **ReviewBench (previous proposal)**: Includes robustness tests but not systematic contradiction detection. 4) **Fact-checking benchmarks**: Evaluate factual consistency but typically for news/articles, not scientific papers with technical content. Our proposal is novel in focusing specifically on internal contradiction detection within scientific papers as a core competency for AI reviewers, with controlled injection of contradictions to enable systematic evaluation.", "Abstract": "As AI systems increasingly assist in peer review, it is crucial to evaluate their ability to perform critical reasoning tasks beyond surface-level faithfulness. One such task is detecting internal contradictions within scientific papers—including text-text inconsistencies, text-figure mismatches, and overclaims relative to evidence. We introduce ContraReview, a benchmark designed to systematically evaluate AI reviewers on contradiction detection. We curate a dataset of 150 real CS arXiv papers and create modified versions with carefully injected contradictions: (1) text-text contradictions (e.g., conflicting claims between abstract and results), (2) text-figure mismatches (e.g., figure shows different trend than described), and (3) overclaims (e.g., claiming SOTA without proper evidence). Each paper has both original and contradicted versions. We evaluate state-of-the-art LLMs and VLMs using the Ai-Review framework, prompting them to review papers and specifically flag any contradictions or inconsistencies found. We measure detection accuracy, precision/recall for contradiction identification, and the quality of reasoning about contradictions. Our results reveal significant gaps: while models achieve high faithfulness scores on clean papers, their contradiction detection performance drops substantially, especially for subtle text-figure mismatches. ContraReview provides a focused testbed for improving AI reviewers' critical reasoning capabilities and highlights the need for specialized training or prompting strategies for contradiction detection.", "Experiments": "1. **Dataset Creation**: Select 150 CS arXiv papers (CS.CL, CS.LG, CS.CV) with clear figures/tables. For each paper, create 3 contradicted versions: (a) **Text-Text**: Modify one sentence in Results to contradict a claim in Abstract (e.g., change 'improves by 5%' to 'improves by 2%'). (b) **Text-Figure**: Modify a figure caption or description to mismatch the actual figure (e.g., claim 'increasing trend' when figure shows decreasing). (c) **Overclaim**: Add an unsupported claim (e.g., 'Our method outperforms all previous work' without evidence in results). Keep original versions as controls. 2. **Evaluation Protocol**: Use Ai-Review prompt template augmented with explicit instruction: 'Please review this paper and specifically identify any internal contradictions, inconsistencies between text and figures, or overclaims not supported by evidence.' Run each model (GPT-4, Claude 3, Gemini, Llama 3) on all versions. 3. **Metrics**: (i) **Contradiction Detection Accuracy**: Binary classification of whether model flags the injected contradiction. (ii) **Precision/Recall/F1**: For identifying specific contradiction sentences/locations. (iii) **Reasoning Quality**: Human evaluation (1-5 scale) of explanation quality for flagged contradictions. (iv) **False Positive Rate**: On original (non-contradicted) papers. (v) **Ablation**: Compare VLM (receives figures) vs LLM (text-only) performance on text-figure mismatches. 4. **Analysis**: Statistical analysis of performance across contradiction types, model families, and paper domains. Identify common failure modes.", "Risk Factors and Limitations": "1. **Contradiction Design**: Artificially injected contradictions may differ from naturally occurring ones. Mitigation: Use realistic contradiction patterns observed in real paper reviews. 2. **Annotation Cost**: Human evaluation of reasoning quality is labor-intensive. Mitigation: Use expert annotators for a subset and develop automatic proxies. 3. **Model Sensitivity**: Models may be overly sensitive and flag minor inconsistencies as contradictions. We measure false positive rate on original papers. 4. **Domain Specificity**: Focused on CS papers; may not generalize to other fields. Explicitly note as limitation. 5. **Prompt Dependence**: Performance may heavily depend on prompting. We test multiple prompt variants and report best. 6. **Scale**: 150 papers may be limited but sufficient for initial benchmark; can expand later."}}
