s detecting internal contradictions within scientific papers—including text-text inconsistencies, text-figure mismatches, and overclaims relative to evidence. We introduce ContraReview, a benchmark designed to systematically evaluate AI reviewers on contradiction detection. We curate a dataset of 150 real CS arXiv papers and create modified versions with carefully injected contradictions: (1) text-text contradictions (e.g., conflicting claims between abstract and results), (2) text-figure mismatches (e.g., figure shows different trend than described), and (3) overclaims (e.g., claiming SOTA without proper evidence). Each paper has both original and contradicted versions. We evaluate state-of-the-art LLMs and VLMs using the Ai-Review framework, prompting them to review papers and specifically flag any contradictions or inconsistencies found. We measure detection accuracy, precision/recall for contradiction identification, and the quality of reasoning about contradictions. Our results reveal significant gaps: while models achieve high faithfulness scores on clean papers, their contradiction detection performance drops substantially, especially for subtle text-figure mismatches. ContraReview provides a focused testbed for improving AI reviewers' critical reasoning capabilities and highlights the need for specialized training or prompting strategies for contradiction detection.", 'Experiments': "1. **Dataset Creation**: Select 150 CS arXiv papers (CS.CL, CS.LG, CS.CV) with clear figures/tables. For each paper, create 3 contradicted versions: (a) **Text-Text**: Modify one sentence in Results to contradict a claim in Abstract (e.g., change 'improves by 5%' to 'improves by 2%'). (b) **Text-Figure**: Modify a figure caption or description to mismatch the actual figure (e.g., claim 'increasing trend' when figure shows decreasing). (c) **Overclaim**: Add an unsupported claim (e.g., 'Our method outperforms all previous work' without evidence in results). Keep original versions as controls. 2. **Evaluation Protocol**: Use Ai-Review prompt template augmented with explicit instruction: 'Please review this paper and specifically identify any internal contradictions, inconsistencies between text and figures, or overclaims not supported by evidence.' Run each model (GPT-4, Claude 3, Gemini, Llama 3) on all versions. 3. **Metrics**: (i) **Contradiction Detection Accuracy**: Binary classification of whether model flags the injected contradiction. (ii) **Precision/Recall/F1**: For identifying specific contradiction sentences/locations. (iii) **Reasoning Quality**: Human evaluation (1-5 scale) of explanation quality for flagged contradictions. (iv) **False Positive Rate**: On original (non-contradicted) papers. (v) **Ablation**: Compare VLM (receives figures) vs LLM (text-only) performance on text-figure mismatches. 4. **Analysis**: Statistical analysis of performance across contradiction types, model families, and paper domains. Identify common failure modes.", 'Risk Factors and Limitations': '1. **Contradiction Design**: Artificially injected contradictions may differ from naturally occurring ones. Mitigation: Use realistic contradiction patterns observed in real paper reviews. 2. **Annotation Cost**: Human evaluation of reasoning quality is labor-intensive. Mitigation: Use expert annotators for a subset and develop automatic proxies. 3. **Model Sensitivity**: Models may be overly sensitive and flag minor inconsistencies as contradictions. We measure false positive rate on original papers. 4. **Domain Specificity**: Focused on CS papers; may not generalize to other fields. Explicitly note as limitation. 5. **Prompt Dependence**: Performance may heavily depend on prompting. We test multiple prompt variants and report best. 6. **Scale**: 150 papers may be limited but sufficient for initial benchmark; can expand later.'}
