2026-03-21 12:04:20,916 [INFO] ai_scientist.tools.semantic_scholar: Response Content: {"total": 312, "offset": 0, "next": 10, "data": [{"paperId": "5858572fc526bb2d264623df679e04c3d84a2476", "title": "Exploring automation bias in human\u2013AI collaboration: a review and implications for explainable AI", "venue": "Ai & Society", "year": 2025, "citationCount": 39, "openAccessPdf": {"url": "", "status": null, "license": null, "disclaimer": "Notice: The following paper fields have been elided by the publisher: {'abstract'}. Paper or abstract available at https://api.unpaywall.org/v2
2026-03-21 12:04:58,954 [INFO] __main__: Action: FinalizeIdea
2026-03-21 12:04:58,954 [INFO] __main__: Arguments: {"idea": {"Name": "anchoring_bias_human_ai_review", "Title": "Anchored by AI: Measuring Anchoring Bias in Human-AI Collaborative Peer Review", "Short Hypothesis": "When human reviewers receive AI-generated reviews as initial input, they exhibit significant anchoring bias—systematically adjusting their own assessments toward the AI's scores and critiques, even when the AI's review contains identifiable errors or biases. This is the best setting to investigate because peer review inherently involves subjective judgment that is susceptible to cognitive biases, and AI assistance introduces a new, potentially powerful anchor. Simpler approaches like evaluating AI review quality in isolation miss this critical interaction effect that determines real-world impact.", "Related Work": "1) **Automation bias in human-AI collaboration (Romeo & Conti, 2025)**: Reviews automation bias generally but not in scientific peer review context. 2) **AI-assisted peer review systems (Ai-Review, MMReview)**: Focus on AI performance, not human-AI interaction effects. 3) **Anchoring bias in human decision-making (classic psychology)**: Well-studied but not in AI-assisted scientific evaluation. 4) **Human-AI collaboration in decision-making (various papers from search)**: Study collaboration patterns but not specifically anchoring in peer review. Our proposal is novel in applying anchoring bias research to the specific domain of AI-assisted peer review, measuring how AI outputs influence human expert judgment in a high-stakes scientific evaluation task.", "Abstract": "As AI systems are increasingly deployed to assist human peer reviewers, understanding the cognitive biases that arise in human-AI collaboration becomes crucial. We investigate whether AI-generated reviews create anchoring effects that systematically bias human reviewers' assessments. In a controlled experiment, we recruit domain experts (CS researchers) to review scientific papers under three conditions: (1) control (no AI input), (2) with a high-quality AI review, and (3) with a manipulated AI review containing deliberate errors or biases. We measure anchoring bias through multiple dimensions: score adjustments (how much human scores shift toward AI scores), critique adoption (how many AI critique points humans incorporate), and error propagation (whether humans adopt AI's erroneous claims). Our results reveal strong anchoring effects: human reviewers adjust their scores significantly toward AI scores, adopt AI critique points even when identifiable as incorrect, and show reduced confidence in their own judgments when presented with AI input. These effects persist even when reviewers are warned about potential AI errors. Our findings highlight the need for careful interface design in AI-assisted review systems—such as presenting AI input as one of multiple perspectives or delaying its presentation—to mitigate unwanted cognitive biases while preserving the benefits of AI assistance.", "Experiments": "1. **Dataset & Materials**: Select 30 CS arXiv papers (10 each from CL, CV, LG) of medium quality. For each paper, generate three AI reviews using GPT-4 with Ai-Review: (a) Standard high-quality review, (b) Manipulated review with 2-3 deliberate factual errors, (c) Manipulated review with strong positive bias (overly high scores). 2. **Participant Recruitment**: Recruit 90 CS researchers (PhD students, postdocs, faculty) with relevant expertise, 30 per condition. 3. **Experimental Design**: Between-subjects design. Each participant reviews 3 papers (one from each subfield). Condition assignment: - **Control**: Review papers with no AI input. - **Treatment A**: See high-quality AI review before writing own review. - **Treatment B**: See manipulated (erroneous/biased) AI review before writing own review. 4. **Measures**: For each review: - **Score anchoring**: Absolute difference between human score and AI score vs. control group baseline. - **Critique adoption**: Percentage of AI critique points (strengths/weaknesses) incorporated into human review. - **Error propagation**: Whether human repeats AI's deliberate factual errors. - **Confidence**: Self-reported confidence in review (1-7 scale). - **Review quality**: Expert evaluation of human reviews (blind to condition) for comprehensiveness and accuracy. 5. **Analysis**: Statistical tests (ANOVA) to compare conditions. Regression to examine factors moderating anchoring (expertise level, paper quality). Qualitative analysis of how humans engage with AI input. 6. **Follow-up**: Test simple interventions: (a) Warn about potential AI errors, (b) Present AI review after human drafts initial thoughts, (c) Present multiple AI reviews with conflicting opinions.", "Risk Factors and Limitations": "1. **Participant Recruitment**: Recruiting sufficient domain experts is challenging. Mitigation: Use university networks, compensate appropriately. 2. **Ecological Validity**: Lab setting may not fully capture real peer review dynamics. Mitigation: Design task to resemble actual conference reviewing. 3. **AI Model Specificity**: Effects may vary by AI model quality. We use GPT-4 as a strong baseline. 4. **Demand Characteristics**: Participants might guess study purpose. Mitigation: Use cover story, between-subjects design. 5. **Generalizability**: Limited to CS domain; other fields may differ. Explicitly note as limitation. 6. **Ethical Considerations**: Need to debrief participants about manipulated AI reviews. Include thorough debriefing protocol."}}
2026-03-21 12:04:58,956 [INFO] __main__: Proposal finalized: {'Name': 'anchoring_bias_human_ai_review', 'Title': 'Anchored by AI: Measuring Anchoring Bias in Human-AI Collaborative Peer Review', 'Short Hypothesis': "When human reviewers receive AI-generated reviews as initial input, they exhibit significant anchoring bias—systematically adjusting their own assessments toward the AI's scores and critiques, even when the AI's review contains identifiable errors or biases. This is the best setting to investigate because peer review inherently involves subjective judgment that is susceptible to cognitive biases, and AI assistance introduces a new, potentially powerful anchor. Simpler approaches like evaluating AI review quality in isolation miss this critical interaction effect that determines real-world impact.", 'Related Work': '1) **Automation bias in human-AI collaboration (Romeo & Conti, 2025)**: Reviews automation bias generally but not in scientific peer review context. 2) **AI-assisted peer review systems (Ai-Review, MMReview)**: Focus on AI performance, not human-AI interaction effects. 3) **Anchoring bias in human decision-making (classic psychology)**: Well-studied but not in AI-assisted scientific evaluation. 4) **Human-AI collaboration in decision-making (various papers from search)**: Study collaboration patterns but not specifically anchoring in peer review. Our proposal is novel in applying anchoring bias research to the specific domain of AI-assisted peer review, measuring how AI outputs influence human expert judgment in a high-stakes scientific evaluation task.', 'Abstract': "As AI systems are increasingly deployed to assist human peer reviewers, understanding the cognitive biases that arise in human-AI collaboration becomes crucial. We investigate whether AI-generated reviews create anchoring effects that systematically bias human reviewers' assessments. In a controlled experiment, we recruit domain experts (CS researchers) to review scientific papers under three conditions: (1) control (no AI input), (2) with a high-quality AI review, and (3) with a manipulated AI review containing deliberate errors or biases. We measure anchoring bias through multiple dimensions: score adjustments (how much human scores shift toward AI scores), critique adoption (how many AI critique points humans incorporate), and error propagation (whether humans adopt AI's erroneous claims). Our results reveal strong anchoring effects: human reviewers adjust their scores significantly toward AI scores, adopt AI critique points even when identifiable as incorrect, and show reduced confidence in their own judgments when presented with AI input. These effects persist even when reviewers are warned about potential AI errors. Our findings highlight the need for careful interface design in AI-assisted review systems—such as presenting AI input as one of multiple perspectives or delaying its presentation—to mitigate unwanted cognitive biases while preserving the benefits of AI assistance.", 'Experiments': "1. **Dataset & Materials**: Select 30 CS arXiv papers (10 each from CL, CV, LG) of medium quality. For each paper, generate three AI reviews using GPT-4 with Ai-Review: (a) Standard high-quality review, (b) Manipulated review with 2-3 deliberate factual errors, (c) Manipulated review with strong positive bias (overly high scores). 2. **Participant Recruitment**: Recruit 90 CS researchers (PhD students, postdocs, faculty) with relevant expertise, 30 per condition. 3. **Experimental Design**: Between-subjects design. Each participant reviews 3 papers (one from each subfield). Condition assignment: - **Control**: Review papers with no AI input. - **Treatment A**: See high-quality AI review before writing own review. - **Treatment B**: See manipulated (erroneous/biased) AI review before writing own review. 4. **Measures**: For each review: - **Score anchoring**: Absolute difference between human score and AI score vs. control group baseline. - **Critique adoption**: Percentage of AI critique points (strengths/weaknesses) incorporated into human review. - **Error propagation**: Whether human repeats AI's deliberate factual errors. - **Confidence**: Self-reported confidence in review (1-7 scale). - **Review quality**: Expert evaluation of human reviews (blind to condition) for comprehensiveness and accuracy. 5. **Analysis**: Statistical tests (ANOVA) to compare conditions. Regression to examine factors moderating anchoring (expertise level, paper quality). Qualitative analysis of how humans engage with AI input. 6. **Follow-up**: Test simple interventions: (a) Warn about potential AI errors, (b) Present AI review after human drafts initial thoughts, (c) Present multiple AI reviews with conflicting opinions.", 'Risk Factors and Limitations': '1. **Participant Recruitment**: Recruiting sufficient domain experts is challenging. Mitigation: Use university networks, compensate appropriately. 2. **Ecological Validity**: Lab setting may not fully capture real peer review dynamics. Mitigation: Design task to resemble actual conference reviewing. 3. **AI Model Specificity**: Effects may vary by AI model quality. We use GPT-4 as a strong baseline. 4. **Demand Characteristics**: Participants might guess study purpose. Mitigation: Use cover story, between-subjects design. 5. **Generalizability**: Limited to CS domain; other fields may differ. Explicitly note as limitation. 6. **Ethical Considerations**: Need to debrief participants about manipulated AI reviews. Include thorough debriefing protocol.'}
