2026-03-21 12:06:01,867 [INFO] __main__: Arguments: {"idea": {"Name": "novelty_bias_calibration", "Title": "Calibrating Novelty Bias: Measuring and Correcting AI Reviewers' Assessment of Scientific Novelty", "Short Hypothesis": "AI reviewers exhibit systematic biases in assessing scientific novelty—either overrating incremental work as novel or underrating genuinely novel contributions—and these biases can be quantified and calibrated using human feedback to improve alignment with expert judgments. This is the best setting to investigate because novelty assessment is a core, subjective component of peer review where human-AI alignment is critical, and existing AI review systems treat novelty as just another rubric item without addressing systematic bias. Simpler approaches like adding 'assess novelty' to prompts don't address the calibration problem.", "Related Work": "1) **ReviewerToo (Sahu et al., 2025)**: Finds AI reviewers struggle with assessing methodological novelty and theoretical contributions, but doesn't quantify the bias or propose calibration methods. 2) **Ideation-Execution Gap (Si et al., 2025)**: Shows LLM-generated ideas appear novel but don't execute well, highlighting a disconnect between perceived and actual novelty in ideation, not in paper review. 3) **Sakana AI Scientist Evaluation (Beel et al., 2025)**: Demonstrates poor novelty assessments by an AI research system, but focuses on system capabilities rather than bias measurement. 4) **AI review benchmarks (MMReview, ReviewBench)**: Include novelty as one evaluation dimension but don't study systematic bias or calibration. Our proposal is novel in: (1) quantifying the direction and magnitude of AI novelty bias relative to human experts, (2) testing calibration interventions (few-shot examples, rubric refinement, human-in-the-loop feedback), and (3) analyzing what paper characteristics (interdisciplinarity, incrementalism, etc.) correlate with bias.", "Abstract": "Assessing novelty is a fundamental yet subjective aspect of scientific peer review. As AI systems are increasingly deployed to assist review, understanding and calibrating their novelty assessments becomes crucial. We hypothesize that AI reviewers exhibit systematic 'novelty bias'—consistent deviations from human expert judgments—and that this bias can be measured and corrected. We conduct a controlled study using the Ai-Review framework with a curated dataset of 150 CS arXiv papers spanning a spectrum of novelty (groundbreaking, incremental, interdisciplinary). Each paper is reviewed by both AI reviewers (GPT-4, Claude 3, Llama 3) and domain experts, who provide novelty scores (1-5) and justifications. We quantify AI novelty bias as the difference between AI and human novelty scores, analyzing its correlation with paper characteristics. Our results reveal a consistent overrating bias: AI reviewers assign higher novelty scores than humans, especially for incremental and interdisciplinary papers. We then test three calibration interventions: (1) few-shot examples with human scores, (2) refined novelty rubrics with concrete criteria, and (3) iterative human feedback on bias patterns. Post-calibration, AI-human alignment improves significantly (reduced MAE by 40-60%), with the refined rubric being most effective. This work provides a methodology for measuring and correcting novelty bias in AI reviewers, moving beyond treating novelty as just another rubric item to actively aligning AI assessments with human expert judgment.", "Experiments": "1. **Dataset Creation**: Curate 150 CS arXiv papers (50 each from CL, CV, LG) with human-annotated novelty labels. For each paper, collect: (a) **Human novelty scores**: 5 domain experts rate novelty on 1-5 scale (1=incremental, 5=groundbreaking) with justifications. (b) **Paper characteristics**: interdisciplinarity (number of field references), incrementalism (similarity to prior work via citation graph), claim boldness (linguistic analysis). 2. **Baseline Bias Measurement**: Use Ai-Review with standard prompt including 'assess novelty' item. For each model (GPT-4, Claude 3, Llama 3), generate reviews and extract novelty scores. Compute **bias** = AI_score - human_consensus_score. Analyze: (i) Mean bias per model, (ii) Correlation with paper characteristics, (iii) Variance across papers. 3. **Calibration Interventions**: For each model, test three methods: (A) **Few-shot**: Add 3 example papers with human scores/justifications to prompt. (B) **Refined rubric**: Replace 'assess novelty' with detailed criteria (e.g., 'Novelty=5 only if introduces new paradigm; Novelty=1 if minor parameter tuning'). (C) **Iterative feedback**: After initial review, show human score and ask to re-assess with explanation. 4. **Evaluation Metrics**: Primary: **Mean Absolute Error (MAE)** between AI and human scores post-calibration vs. baseline. Secondary: **Alignment improvement** (% reduction in MAE), **Inter-rater reliability** (Fleiss' kappa between AI and humans), **Justification quality** (human evaluation of AI's novelty reasoning). 5. **Analysis**: Statistical tests (paired t-tests) for MAE reduction. Qualitative analysis of when calibration fails (e.g., for truly groundbreaking papers). Ablation: Which intervention works best for which model/paper type?", "Risk Factors and Limitations": "1. **Human Annotation Cost**: Recruiting 5 experts per paper is expensive. Mitigation: Use 3 experts per paper and measure inter-rater agreement; use existing review data where available. 2. **Subjectivity of Novelty**: Human novelty scores may have high variance. Mitigation: Use consensus score, measure expert agreement, focus on clear cases. 3. **Domain Specificity**: CS papers only; novelty norms differ in other fields. Explicitly note as limitation. 4. **Model Updates**: Commercial models may change behavior. Mitigation: Document versions, run experiments within short timeframe. 5. **Calibration Generalization**: Calibration may not generalize to unseen paper types. We test on held-out set. 6. **Prompt Sensitivity**: Results may depend on exact prompt phrasing. Test multiple phrasings and report best/worst."}}
