as Measurement**: Use Ai-Review with standard prompt including 'assess novelty' item. For each model (GPT-4, Claude 3, Llama 3), generate reviews and extract novelty scores. Compute **bias** = AI_score - human_consensus_score. Analyze: (i) Mean bias per model, (ii) Correlation with paper characteristics, (iii) Variance across papers. 3. **Calibration Interventions**: For each model, test three methods: (A) **Few-shot**: Add 3 example papers with human scores/justifications to prompt. (B) **Refined rubric**: Replace 'assess novelty' with detailed criteria (e.g., 'Novelty=5 only if introduces new paradigm; Novelty=1 if minor parameter tuning'). (C) **Iterative feedback**: After initial review, show human score and ask to re-assess with explanation. 4. **Evaluation Metrics**: Primary: **Mean Absolute Error (MAE)** between AI and human scores post-calibration vs. baseline. Secondary: **Alignment improvement** (% reduction in MAE), **Inter-rater reliability** (Fleiss' kappa between AI and humans), **Justification quality** (human evaluation of AI's novelty reasoning). 5. **Analysis**: Statistical tests (paired t-tests) for MAE reduction. Qualitative analysis of when calibration fails (e.g., for truly groundbreaking papers). Ablation: Which intervention works best for which model/paper type?", 'Risk Factors and Limitations': '1. **Human Annotation Cost**: Recruiting 5 experts per paper is expensive. Mitigation: Use 3 experts per paper and measure inter-rater agreement; use existing review data where available. 2. **Subjectivity of Novelty**: Human novelty scores may have high variance. Mitigation: Use consensus score, measure expert agreement, focus on clear cases. 3. **Domain Specificity**: CS papers only; novelty norms differ in other fields. Explicitly note as limitation. 4. **Model Updates**: Commercial models may change behavior. Mitigation: Document versions, run experiments within short timeframe. 5. **Calibration Generalization**: Calibration may not generalize to unseen paper types. We test on held-out set. 6. **Prompt Sensitivity**: Results may depend on exact prompt phrasing. Test multiple phrasings and report best/worst.'}
