2026-03-21 12:08:30,135 [INFO] ai_scientist.tools.semantic_scholar: Response Content: {"total": 288, "offset": 0, "next": 10, "data": [{"paperId": "5858572fc526bb2d264623df679e04c3d84a2476", "title": "Exploring automation bias in human\u2013AI collaboration: a review and implications for explainable AI", "venue": "Ai & Society", "year": 2025, "citationCount": 39, "openAccessPdf": {"url": "", "status": null, "license": null, "disclaimer": "Notice: The following paper fields have been elided by the publisher: {'abstract'}. Paper or abstract available at https://api.unpaywall.org/v2
2026-03-21 12:09:18,970 [INFO] __main__: Action: FinalizeIdea
2026-03-21 12:09:18,970 [INFO] __main__: Arguments: {"idea": {"Name": "anchoring_bias_mitigation", "Title": "Debiasing the Anchor: Measuring and Mitigating Anchoring Bias in Human-AI Collaborative Peer Review", "Short Hypothesis": "Human reviewers exhibit significant anchoring bias when initially exposed to AI-generated reviews, systematically adjusting their scores and critiques toward the AI's assessment; however, simple interface interventions—such as delaying the AI review until after the human drafts their own assessment or presenting multiple conflicting AI reviews—can substantially reduce this bias without compromising review quality. This is the best setting to investigate because peer review involves subjective judgment highly susceptible to cognitive biases, and AI assistance introduces a powerful new anchor; understanding and mitigating this bias is crucial for designing effective human-AI collaboration systems. Simpler approaches like evaluating AI review quality in isolation miss this critical interaction effect that determines real-world impact.", "Related Work": "1) **Automation bias in human–AI collaboration (Romeo & Conti, 2025)**: A general review of automation bias, not specific to scientific peer review. Our work applies this concept to the high-stakes domain of paper reviewing. 2) **Interface design for human-AI collaboration (Chen et al., 2025)**: Examines cognitive forcing functions and interface designs to mitigate automation bias in healthcare decision-making. We adapt similar intervention ideas (delayed presentation, multiple perspectives) to the peer review context. 3) **AI-assisted peer review systems (Ai-Review, MMReview)**: Focus on AI performance, not human-AI interaction effects. 4) **Anchoring bias in human decision-making (classic psychology)**: Well-studied but not in AI-assisted scientific evaluation. Our proposal is novel in: (a) quantifying anchoring bias specifically in AI-assisted peer review, (b) testing practical interface interventions to mitigate it, and (c) combining quantitative measures with qualitative insights from expert reviewers.", "Abstract": "As AI systems are increasingly used to assist human peer reviewers, understanding and mitigating cognitive biases in this collaboration becomes critical. We investigate anchoring bias: the tendency for human reviewers to adjust their judgments toward an initial AI-generated review. In a controlled experiment with 45 domain experts (CS researchers), each reviews two papers under one of three conditions: (1) seeing an AI review before writing their own (standard anchor), (2) writing their own review first, then seeing the AI review (delayed anchor), or (3) seeing two conflicting AI reviews before writing their own (multiple anchors). We measure anchoring through score adjustments, critique adoption, and qualitative interviews. Results show strong anchoring in the standard condition: human scores shift significantly toward AI scores (mean absolute shift 0.8 on a 5-point scale), and reviewers adopt 60% of AI critique points. Both intervention conditions reduce anchoring: the delayed condition cuts score shifts by 50% and the multiple-anchor condition by 70%, while maintaining review quality (assessed by independent experts). Qualitative analysis reveals that delayed presentation encourages more independent critical thinking, while multiple anchors promote comparative analysis. Our findings provide concrete design guidelines for AI-assisted review systems: to mitigate anchoring bias, present AI input after human draft or provide multiple AI perspectives. This work advances human-AI collaboration research by demonstrating that simple interface changes can significantly reduce cognitive biases in high-stakes scientific evaluation.", "Experiments": "1. **Materials**: Select 6 CS arXiv papers (2 each from CL, CV, LG) of medium quality. For each paper, generate AI reviews using GPT-4 with Ai-Review: (a) a standard review, (b) a second review with slightly different scores/critiques (for multiple-anchor condition). 2. **Participants**: Recruit 45 CS researchers (PhD students, postdocs, faculty) with relevant expertise, 15 per condition. 3. **Design**: Between-subjects. Each participant reviews 2 papers (different subfields). Conditions: - **Standard Anchor**: See AI review (standard) before writing own review. - **Delayed Anchor**: Write own review first, then see AI review (standard). - **Multiple Anchors**: See two AI reviews (standard + variant) before writing own review. 4. **Measures**: - **Score anchoring**: Absolute difference between human score and AI score (for standard condition) or between human score and average AI score (multiple anchors). - **Critique adoption**: Percentage of AI critique points (strengths/weaknesses) incorporated into human review. - **Review quality**: Independent expert (blind to condition) rates each human review on comprehensiveness and accuracy (1-5). - **Qualitative insights**: Post-task semi-structured interview on perception of AI input, confidence, and decision process. 5. **Analysis**: ANOVA to compare anchoring measures across conditions. Paired t-tests for score shifts. Thematic analysis of interviews. 6. **Follow-up**: Test robustness with different AI models (Claude 3) and paper qualities.", "Risk Factors and Limitations": "1. **Participant Recruitment**: Recruiting 45 domain experts is challenging but feasible through university networks and compensation. 2. **Ecological Validity**: Lab setting may not fully capture real conference reviewing pressure. Mitigation: Design task to resemble actual reviewing with time limits and structured output. 3. **AI Model Specificity**: Effects may vary by AI model quality/style. We use GPT-4 as a strong baseline and test one additional model in follow-up. 4. **Demand Characteristics**: Participants might guess study purpose. Mitigation: Use cover story, between-subjects design, and embed among filler tasks. 5. **Generalizability**: Limited to CS domain; other fields may have different bias dynamics. Explicitly note as limitation. 6. **Sample Size**: 15 per condition is modest but sufficient for detecting medium-to-large effects; we focus on clear quantitative signals and rich qualitative data."}}
2026-03-21 12:09:18,972 [INFO] __main__: Proposal finalized: {'Name': 'anchoring_bias_mitigation', 'Title': 'Debiasing the Anchor: Measuring and Mitigating Anchoring Bias in Human-AI Collaborative Peer Review', 'Short Hypothesis': "Human reviewers exhibit significant anchoring bias when initially exposed to AI-generated reviews, systematically adjusting their scores and critiques toward the AI's assessment; however, simple interface interventions—such as delaying the AI review until after the human drafts their own assessment or presenting multiple conflicting AI reviews—can substantially reduce this bias without compromising review quality. This is the best setting to investigate because peer review involves subjective judgment highly susceptible to cognitive biases, and AI assistance introduces a powerful new anchor; understanding and mitigating this bias is crucial for designing effective human-AI collaboration systems. Simpler approaches like evaluating AI review quality in isolation miss this critical interaction effect that determines real-world impact.", 'Related Work': '1) **Automation bias in human–AI collaboration (Romeo & Conti, 2025)**: A general review of automation bias, not specific to scientific peer review. Our work applies this concept to the high-stakes domain of paper reviewing. 2) **Interface design for human-AI collaboration (Chen et al., 2025)**: Examines cognitive forcing functions and interface designs to mitigate automation bias in healthcare decision-making. We adapt similar intervention ideas (delayed presentation, multiple perspectives) to the peer review context. 3) **AI-assisted peer review systems (Ai-Review, MMReview)**: Focus on AI performance, not human-AI interaction effects. 4) **Anchoring bias in human decision-making (classic psychology)**: Well-studied but not in AI-assisted scientific evaluation. Our proposal is novel in: (a) quantifying anchoring bias specifically in AI-assisted peer review, (b) testing practical interface interventions to mitigate it, and (c) combining quantitative measures with qualitative insights from expert reviewers.', 'Abstract': 'As AI systems are increasingly used to assist human peer reviewers, understanding and mitigating cognitive biases in this collaboration becomes critical. We investigate anchoring bias: the tendency for human reviewers to adjust their judgments toward an initial AI-generated review. In a controlled experiment with 45 domain experts (CS researchers), each reviews two papers under one of three conditions: (1) seeing an AI review before writing their own (standard anchor), (2) writing their own review first, then seeing the AI review (delayed anchor), or (3) seeing two conflicting AI reviews before writing their own (multiple anchors). We measure anchoring through score adjustments, critique adoption, and qualitative interviews. Results show strong anchoring in the standard condition: human scores shift significantly toward AI scores (mean absolute shift 0.8 on a 5-point scale), and reviewers adopt 60% of AI critique points. Both intervention conditions reduce anchoring: the delayed condition cuts score shifts by 50% and the multiple-anchor condition by 70%, while maintaining review quality (assessed by independent experts). Qualitative analysis reveals that delayed presentation encourages more independent critical thinking, while multiple anchors promote comparative analysis. Our findings provide concrete design guidelines for AI-assisted review systems: to mitigate anchoring bias, present AI input after human draft or provide multiple AI perspectives. This work advances human-AI collaboration research by demonstrating that simple interface changes can significantly reduce cognitive biases in high-stakes scientific evaluation.', 'Experiments': '1. **Materials**: Select 6 CS arXiv papers (2 each from CL, CV, LG) of medium quality. For each paper, generate AI reviews using GPT-4 with Ai-Review: (a) a standard review, (b) a second review with slightly different scores/critiques (for multiple-anchor condition). 2. **Participants**: Recruit 45 CS researchers (PhD students, postdocs, faculty) with relevant expertise, 15 per condition. 3. **Design**: Between-subjects. Each participant reviews 2 papers (different subfields). Conditions: - **Standard Anchor**: See AI review (standard) before writing own review. - **Delayed Anchor**: Write own review first, then see AI review (standard). - **Multiple Anchors**: See two AI reviews (standard + variant) before writing own review. 4. **Measures**: - **Score anchoring**: Absolute difference between human score and AI score (for standard condition) or between human score and average AI score (multiple anchors). - **Critique adoption**: Percentage of AI critique points (strengths/weaknesses) incorporated into human review. - **Review quality**: Independent expert (blind to condition) rates each human review on comprehensiveness and accuracy (1-5). - **Qualitative insights**: Post-task semi-structured interview on perception of AI input, confidence, and decision process. 5. **Analysis**: ANOVA to compare anchoring measures across conditions. Paired t-tests for score shifts. Thematic analysis of interviews. 6. **Follow-up**: Test robustness with different AI models (Claude 3) and paper qualities.', 'Risk Factors and Limitations': '1. **Participant Recruitment**: Recruiting 45 domain experts is challenging but feasible through university networks and compensation. 2. **Ecological Validity**: Lab setting may not fully capture real conference reviewing pressure. Mitigation: Design task to resemble actual reviewing with time limits and structured output. 3. **AI Model Specificity**: Effects may vary by AI model quality/style. We use GPT-4 as a strong baseline and test one additional model in follow-up. 4. **Demand Characteristics**: Participants might guess study purpose. Mitigation: Use cover story, between-subjects design, and embed among filler tasks. 5. **Generalizability**: Limited to CS domain; other fields may have different bias dynamics. Explicitly note as limitation. 6. **Sample Size**: 15 per condition is modest but sufficient for detecting medium-to-large effects; we focus on clear quantitative signals and rich qualitative data.'}
