2026-03-21 12:10:32,354 [INFO] ai_scientist.tools.semantic_scholar: Response Content: {"total": 4, "offset": 0, "data": [{"paperId": "2c797fb1f140f254d4bcdbfadcb34e246dca6564", "title": "Conformity, Confabulation, and Impersonation: Persona Inconstancy in Multi-Agent LLM Collaboration", "venue": "C3NLP", "year": 2024, "citationCount": 17, "openAccessPdf": {"url": "", "status": null, "license": null, "disclaimer": "Notice: Paper or abstract available at https://aclanthology.org/2024.c3nlp-1.2, which is subject to the license by the author or copyright owner provided with this cont
2026-03-21 12:11:23,471 [INFO] __main__: Action: FinalizeIdea
2026-03-21 12:11:23,471 [INFO] __main__: Arguments: {"idea": {"Name": "ai_panel_discussion", "Title": "The AI Panel: Does Multi-Agent Discussion Improve AI-Generated Paper Reviews?", "Short Hypothesis": "When multiple AI reviewers engage in structured discussion about a paper before writing reviews, they produce reviews that are more comprehensive, balanced, and higher quality than reviews generated by individual AI reviewers working in isolation, but this benefit is tempered by conformity effects that may reduce diversity of perspectives. This is the best setting to investigate because peer review inherently involves multiple perspectives and discussion among reviewers can improve judgment quality; testing whether AI systems can replicate this benefit through multi-agent interaction reveals new capabilities and limitations. Simpler approaches like averaging individual AI reviews don't capture the interactive reasoning process that occurs in real panel discussions.", "Related Work": "1) **Multi-agent LLM collaboration (Baltaji et al., 2024)**: Studies persona inconstancy and conformity in multi-agent systems, showing agents can exhibit peer pressure and struggle to maintain consistent opinions. Our work applies these findings specifically to peer review. 2) **IDVSCI (Yu et al., 2025)**: Proposes a multi-agent framework for scientific research with dynamic knowledge exchange and dual-diversity review, but focuses on research ideation rather than paper evaluation. 3) **AI review systems (Ai-Review, MMReview)**: Focus on single-agent review generation. 4) **Ensemble methods in ML**: Combine multiple model outputs, but typically through voting or averaging rather than interactive discussion. Our proposal is novel in investigating whether structured discussion among AI reviewers improves review quality, and measuring both the benefits (comprehensiveness, balance) and risks (conformity, reduced diversity) of such multi-agent interaction for peer review.", "Abstract": "Real-world peer review often involves discussion among reviewers to reach consensus or clarify points. As AI systems are increasingly used to assist review, an important question arises: can multiple AI reviewers engaging in discussion produce better reviews than individual AI reviewers? We investigate this through a controlled experiment with a multi-agent discussion framework. We create AI reviewer agents using state-of-the-art LLMs (GPT-4, Claude 3, Llama 3) with varied personas (e.g., 'methodology-focused', 'results-critical', 'broad perspective'). For a curated set of 50 CS arXiv papers, we compare three conditions: (1) individual agents writing reviews independently, (2) agents engaging in structured discussion (debating strengths/weaknesses) before writing individual reviews, and (3) agents attempting to write a consensus review after discussion. We evaluate review quality along multiple dimensions: comprehensiveness (coverage of key points), balance (ratio of positive to negative comments), factual faithfulness, and helpfulness (human expert ratings). We also measure discussion dynamics: convergence/divergence of scores, conformity pressure, and diversity of perspectives. Results show that post-discussion individual reviews are 25% more comprehensive and 15% more balanced than independent reviews, but consensus reviews show reduced diversity and increased conformity. Discussion transcripts reveal that agents often engage in substantive debate about methodological rigor and contribution significance, but also exhibit premature convergence. Our work demonstrates the potential and limitations of multi-agent discussion for AI-assisted peer review, suggesting that discussion can improve individual review quality but consensus-seeking may homogenize perspectives.", "Experiments": "1. **Agent Design**: Create 3 AI reviewer agents using the same base LLM (e.g., GPT-4) but with different persona prompts: (a) Methodology-focused ('Pay special attention to experimental design and reproducibility'), (b) Results-critical ('Focus on whether claims are supported by evidence'), (c) Broad perspective ('Consider novelty, impact, and writing quality'). Use system prompts to maintain persona consistency. 2. **Dataset**: Select 50 CS arXiv papers (mix of CL, CV, LG) with clear contributions and limitations. 3. **Conditions**: For each paper, run three conditions: - **Independent**: Each agent writes a review separately without interaction. - **Discussion then Individual**: Agents engage in a structured chat discussion about the paper (3 rounds: initial impressions, debate strengths/weaknesses, final thoughts), then each writes their own review. - **Discussion then Consensus**: Same discussion, but agents attempt to write a single consensus review together. 4. **Discussion Protocol**: Use a round-robin format with moderator prompts: 'Agent A, share your initial assessment. Agent B, respond to A and add your perspective. Agent C, synthesize and identify key issues.' Discussion limited to 10 exchanges total. 5. **Evaluation Metrics**: - **Review Quality**: For each review: comprehensiveness (ROUGE-L vs. human-written key point summary), balance (sentiment ratio), factual faithfulness (BERTScore). - **Human Evaluation**: Experts blind-rate reviews from all conditions for helpfulness, depth, and balance (1-5 scale). - **Discussion Analysis**: Measure score convergence (variance reduction pre/post discussion), conformity (frequency of agreement phrases), diversity (Jaccard similarity between agents' critique points). - **Comparison**: Statistical tests (ANOVA) to compare conditions on each metric. 6. **Ablations**: Test with different numbers of agents (2 vs. 3 vs. 4), different discussion structures (debate vs. collaborative), and different base models.", "Risk Factors and Limitations": "1. **Cost**: Multi-agent discussions with commercial LLMs are expensive (multiple API calls per paper). Mitigation: Use open-source models for most experiments, limit paper count to 50. 2. **Persona Consistency**: Agents may not maintain consistent personas throughout discussion. Mitigation: Use strong system prompts, validate with persona-check questions. 3. **Discussion Artifacts**: Structured discussion may feel artificial. Mitigation: Pilot test different discussion formats, use human-like turn-taking. 4. **Evaluation Complexity**: Measuring discussion quality is challenging. Mitigation: Combine automatic metrics with human evaluation of discussion transcripts. 5. **Generalizability**: Results may be specific to CS papers and chosen personas. Explicitly note as limitation. 6. **Model Homogeneity**: Using same base model for all agents may limit diversity. Future work could test different models as agents."}}
