2026-03-21 12:12:30,110 [INFO] __main__: Arguments: {"idea": {"Name": "format_robustness_review", "Title": "Beyond the PDF: How Document Format and Layout Affect AI-Generated Paper Reviews", "Short Hypothesis": "The format and layout of a scientific paper (e.g., LaTeX vs. Word, single-column vs. double-column, with/without figures) significantly affect the quality of AI-generated reviews, even when the textual content is identical, because parsing and visual grounding introduce noise that degrades understanding. This is the best setting to investigate because AI-assisted review systems must handle real-world format diversity, and current evaluations typically use clean, uniformly formatted text, masking this vulnerability. Simpler approaches like testing on a single format miss this critical robustness dimension.", "Related Work": "1) **DocRefine (Qian et al., 2025)**: A multimodal agent framework for scientific document understanding and editing, but not focused on review generation or format robustness. 2) **PDF ingestion for RAG (Bansal et al., 2025)**: Surveys challenges in parsing complex PDFs for retrieval, but not for generative review tasks. 3) **AI review systems (Ai-Review, MMReview)**: Assume clean input formats; they don't evaluate sensitivity to layout variations. 4) **Document understanding benchmarks**: Exist for tasks like QA or summarization, but not for peer review generation across formats. Our proposal is novel in systematically isolating format/layout as an independent variable to measure its causal impact on AI review quality, providing a robustness check for deployment.", "Abstract": "AI-assisted peer review systems are typically evaluated on clean, uniformly formatted papers, ignoring the reality that submissions come in diverse formats: LaTeX, Word, PDFs with varying layouts, and with or without embedded figures. We hypothesize that these format differences significantly degrade AI review quality even when textual content is identical, due to parsing errors and visual grounding challenges. To test this, we conduct a controlled experiment using the Ai-Review framework. We take a curated set of 50 CS arXiv papers and create multiple format variants for each: (1) LaTeX source, (2) PDF rendered with standard conference template (single-column), (3) PDF with double-column layout, (4) Microsoft Word document (converted), (5) plain text (stripped of formatting), and (6) PDF with simulated OCR errors. For each variant, we generate reviews using state-of-the-art LLMs/VLMs (GPT-4, Claude 3, Gemini) and evaluate review quality along three dimensions: factual faithfulness (BERTScore against source), coverage of key points (ROUGE-L vs. human summary), and consistency (score variance across formats). Results show that format matters: double-column layouts and Word conversions cause significant drops in faithfulness (up to 15% relative), while plain text often performs best. VLMs handling PDFs are more robust to layout changes but still degrade with OCR noise. Our work highlights the need for format-robust parsing in AI review systems and provides a benchmark for evaluating such robustness.", "Experiments": "1. **Dataset & Format Variants**: Select 50 CS arXiv papers (CL, CV, LG) with LaTeX source and figures. For each paper, create 6 format variants: (A) LaTeX source (.tex), (B) PDF (standard single-column, e.g., NeurIPS style), (C) PDF (double-column, e.g., IEEE style), (D) Word document (.docx, converted via pandoc), (E) Plain text (.txt, extracted via pdftotext), (F) PDF with simulated OCR errors (random character swaps/deletions, 5% error rate). Ensure textual content is as identical as possible across variants. 2. **Model & Setup**: Use Ai-Review prompt template. For each (paper, format) pair, generate a review using: (i) Text-only LLM (GPT-4, Claude 3) with text extracted from the format (for PDF/Word, use extraction tool like pdftotext/docx2txt). (ii) VLM (GPT-4V, Gemini Pro Vision) that receives the PDF/Word directly (for formats B, C, F). Run each model on all variants. 3. **Evaluation Metrics**: For each review: - **Factual Faithfulness**: BERTScore F1 between review statements and sentences from the original LaTeX source (ground truth content). - **Coverage**: ROUGE-L F1 between review and a human-written summary of key contributions/limitations (created for each paper). - **Score Consistency**: Variance in overall recommendation score (1-5) across format variants for the same paper and model. - **Format-induced Errors**: Manual analysis of a subset to categorize errors due to formatting (e.g., misordered sections, missing figures, garbled math). 4. **Analysis**: Compute average faithfulness/coverage per format variant and model. Statistical tests (ANOVA) to determine if format has significant effect. Compare text-only LLM vs. VLM performance on PDF variants. Identify which formats are most problematic and why.", "Risk Factors and Limitations": "1. **Content Preservation**: Converting between formats may inadvertently alter content (e.g., math rendering, special characters). Mitigation: Manual spot-checking, use high-fidelity converters (pandoc), and focus on formats where content change is minimal. 2. **Extraction Tool Bias**: Text extraction quality depends on tools (pdftotext, etc.). Mitigation: Use state-of-the-art extractors, report tool versions, and consider this as part of the real-world variability. 3. **Cost**: Running multiple models on 50 papers × 6 formats = 300 reviews per model. Mitigation: Use a subset of models (e.g., GPT-4 for main analysis) and limit paper count. 4. **Generalizability**: Limited to CS papers; format effects may differ for fields with heavy math, tables, or diagrams. Explicitly note as limitation. 5. **Evaluation Metric Limitations**: BERTScore/ROUGE may not capture all qualitative aspects. Supplement with human evaluation for a subset. 6. **Temporal Dynamics**: PDF parsing capabilities of VLMs improve rapidly; results are a snapshot. However, the methodology remains valid for comparative evaluation."}}
