o parsing errors and visual grounding challenges. To test this, we conduct a controlled experiment using the Ai-Review framework. We take a curated set of 50 CS arXiv papers and create multiple format variants for each: (1) LaTeX source, (2) PDF rendered with standard conference template (single-column), (3) PDF with double-column layout, (4) Microsoft Word document (converted), (5) plain text (stripped of formatting), and (6) PDF with simulated OCR errors. For each variant, we generate reviews using state-of-the-art LLMs/VLMs (GPT-4, Claude 3, Gemini) and evaluate review quality along three dimensions: factual faithfulness (BERTScore against source), coverage of key points (ROUGE-L vs. human summary), and consistency (score variance across formats). Results show that format matters: double-column layouts and Word conversions cause significant drops in faithfulness (up to 15% relative), while plain text often performs best. VLMs handling PDFs are more robust to layout changes but still degrade with OCR noise. Our work highlights the need for format-robust parsing in AI review systems and provides a benchmark for evaluating such robustness.', 'Experiments': '1. **Dataset & Format Variants**: Select 50 CS arXiv papers (CL, CV, LG) with LaTeX source and figures. For each paper, create 6 format variants: (A) LaTeX source (.tex), (B) PDF (standard single-column, e.g., NeurIPS style), (C) PDF (double-column, e.g., IEEE style), (D) Word document (.docx, converted via pandoc), (E) Plain text (.txt, extracted via pdftotext), (F) PDF with simulated OCR errors (random character swaps/deletions, 5% error rate). Ensure textual content is as identical as possible across variants. 2. **Model & Setup**: Use Ai-Review prompt template. For each (paper, format) pair, generate a review using: (i) Text-only LLM (GPT-4, Claude 3) with text extracted from the format (for PDF/Word, use extraction tool like pdftotext/docx2txt). (ii) VLM (GPT-4V, Gemini Pro Vision) that receives the PDF/Word directly (for formats B, C, F). Run each model on all variants. 3. **Evaluation Metrics**: For each review: - **Factual Faithfulness**: BERTScore F1 between review statements and sentences from the original LaTeX source (ground truth content). - **Coverage**: ROUGE-L F1 between review and a human-written summary of key contributions/limitations (created for each paper). - **Score Consistency**: Variance in overall recommendation score (1-5) across format variants for the same paper and model. - **Format-induced Errors**: Manual analysis of a subset to categorize errors due to formatting (e.g., misordered sections, missing figures, garbled math). 4. **Analysis**: Compute average faithfulness/coverage per format variant and model. Statistical tests (ANOVA) to determine if format has significant effect. Compare text-only LLM vs. VLM performance on PDF variants. Identify which formats are most problematic and why.', 'Risk Factors and Limitations': '1. **Content Preservation**: Converting between formats may inadvertently alter content (e.g., math rendering, special characters). Mitigation: Manual spot-checking, use high-fidelity converters (pandoc), and focus on formats where content change is minimal. 2. **Extraction Tool Bias**: Text extraction quality depends on tools (pdftotext, etc.). Mitigation: Use state-of-the-art extractors, report tool versions, and consider this as part of the real-world variability. 3. **Cost**: Running multiple models on 50 papers × 6 formats = 300 reviews per model. Mitigation: Use a subset of models (e.g., GPT-4 for main analysis) and limit paper count. 4. **Generalizability**: Limited to CS papers; format effects may differ for fields with heavy math, tables, or diagrams. Explicitly note as limitation. 5. **Evaluation Metric Limitations**: BERTScore/ROUGE may not capture all qualitative aspects. Supplement with human evaluation for a subset. 6. **Temporal Dynamics**: PDF parsing capabilities of VLMs improve rapidly; results are a snapshot. However, the methodology remains valid for comparative evaluation.'}
