bstract': "As AI-generated scientific papers become increasingly common, understanding how AI reviewers assess them is crucial for designing fair and effective peer review systems. While prior work has studied AI reviewers' detection accuracy and bias when evaluating AI-generated content, we hypothesize that AI reviewers employ systematically different reviewing strategies depending on whether they are reviewing AI-generated or human-written papers. We conduct a controlled experiment using the Ai-Review framework with state-of-the-art LLMs (GPT-4, Claude 3, Llama 3). We create a balanced dataset of 100 papers: 50 AI-generated (using GPT-4 to generate papers based on real arXiv abstracts) and 50 human-written (from arXiv CS), matched for topic and approximate quality. Each paper is reviewed by each model. We analyze reviews along multiple dimensions: (1) Linguistic patterns (formality, hedging, sentiment), (2) Focus areas (methodology, results, writing style, novelty), (3) Critique styles (constructive vs. dismissive, specificity), and (4) Confidence expressions. Results reveal significant differences: AI reviewers use more formal language and focus more on writing style when reviewing AI-generated papers, while focusing more on methodological rigor for human-written papers. They also express higher confidence when critiquing AI-generated papers. These differences persist even when controlling for paper quality. Our findings demonstrate that AI reviewers adapt their strategy based on the perceived source of a paper, revealing implicit 'AI-awareness' in LLM behavior and highlighting the need for careful design of AI-assisted review systems to ensure consistent evaluation standards.", 'Experiments': "1. **Dataset Creation**: Create 100 papers: (a) 50 AI-generated: Use GPT-4 to generate full papers (abstract, intro, methods, results, discussion) based on 50 real arXiv CS abstracts (from CL, CV, LG). (b) 50 human-written: Select 50 papers from arXiv CS matching the topics of AI-generated papers. Ensure quality matching via citation percentiles or expert ratings. 2. **Review Generation**: Use Ai-Review framework with standard prompt. For each model (GPT-4, Claude 3, Llama 3), generate reviews for all 100 papers. 3. **Analysis Dimensions & Metrics**: For each review, extract: - **Linguistic Patterns**: Formality score (Flesch-Kincaid), hedging frequency ('might', 'perhaps', 'could'), sentiment distribution (positive/negative/neutral). - **Focus Areas**: Using keyword extraction and topic modeling, identify which sections/aspects receive most attention (methods, results, writing, novelty, etc.). - **Critique Styles**: Classify critiques as constructive (suggesting improvements) vs. dismissive (simply pointing out flaws), measure specificity (word count per critique point). - **Confidence Expressions**: Count definitive vs. uncertain language markers. 4. **Statistical Analysis**: Compare metrics between AI-generated and human-written paper reviews for each model using t-tests/ANOVA. Control for paper quality using regression analysis. 5. **Human Validation**: Have domain experts (n=10) blind-rate a subset of reviews (20 AI-generated, 20 human-written) on perceived focus, constructiveness, and confidence. 6. **Ablation**: Test whether explicitly informing the model about paper source ('This paper may be AI-generated') amplifies differences.", 'Risk Factors and Limitations': '1. **AI Paper Generation Quality**: AI-generated papers may differ systematically from human papers beyond just source. Mitigation: Use human-written abstracts as basis, ensure structural similarity, control for quality via expert ratings. 2. **Model Training Data Contamination**: Models may have seen some human-written papers during training. Mitigation: Use recent papers, check for contamination via n-gram overlap. 3. **Generalizability**: Limited to CS domain; patterns may differ in other fields. Explicitly note as limitation. 4. **Scale**: 100 papers may limit statistical power for some analyses. Mitigation: Focus on clear effect sizes, use multiple models. 5. **Evaluation Metric Subjectivity**: Some metrics (constructiveness, focus areas) require human validation. Mitigation: Use multiple raters, measure inter-rater agreement. 6. **Cost**: Generating 100 papers + 300 reviews (3 models × 100 papers) with commercial LLMs is expensive. Mitigation: Use open-source models for paper generation, focus analysis on one commercial model (GPT-4) with others for validation.'}
