2026-03-21 12:18:43,939 [INFO] __main__: Arguments: {"idea": {"Name": "openness_bias_review", "Title": "The Openness Premium: How AI Reviewers Evaluate Reproducibility and Open Science Practices in Scientific Papers", "Short Hypothesis": "AI reviewers systematically undervalue or misinterpret the importance of reproducibility and open science practices (code availability, data sharing, detailed methods) when evaluating papers, focusing instead on traditional criteria like novelty and results, and this bias can be measured and corrected through targeted prompting that emphasizes open science values. This is the best setting to investigate because modern scientific evaluation increasingly values reproducibility and openness, but AI reviewers trained on historical review data may not reflect this shift. Simpler approaches like adding 'check for code availability' to prompts don't address the deeper issue of how AI weights and integrates openness factors into overall assessment.", "Related Work": "1) **CORE-Bench (Siegel et al., 2024)**: Benchmarks AI agents' ability to computationally reproduce results using provided code/data, but focuses on reproduction execution, not on how AI reviewers evaluate openness as part of peer review. 2) **REPRO-Bench (Hu et al., 2025)**: Evaluates AI agents' ability to assess reproducibility of social science papers with reproduction packages, but again focuses on reproduction assessment, not integration into holistic paper review. 3) **AIRepr (Zeng et al., 2025)**: Evaluates reproducibility of LLM-generated data analysis workflows, not paper review. 4) **AI review systems (Ai-Review, MMReview)**: Generate holistic reviews but don't specifically study how they evaluate openness/reproducibility factors. Our proposal is novel in examining how AI reviewers **value and integrate** openness criteria into their overall paper assessment, measuring bias relative to human experts, and testing interventions to align AI with modern open science values.", "Abstract": "As open science practices become increasingly important in scientific evaluation, understanding how AI reviewers assess reproducibility and openness factors is crucial. We hypothesize that AI reviewers systematically undervalue these factors compared to human experts, focusing instead on traditional criteria like novelty and methodological rigor. To test this, we conduct a controlled experiment using the Ai-Review framework with a curated dataset of 120 CS arXiv papers spanning three openness levels: (1) Fully open (code, data, detailed methods), (2) Partially open (code only), and (3) Closed (no supplementary materials). Each paper is reviewed by both AI reviewers (GPT-4, Claude 3, Llama 3) and domain experts who explicitly rate openness importance. We measure openness bias as the difference between AI and human emphasis on openness factors in reviews, analyzing both quantitative scores and qualitative justifications. Results reveal significant bias: AI reviewers mention openness factors 60% less frequently than human experts and assign them 40% lower weight in overall assessment. This bias persists even when papers have major reproducibility issues. We then test three calibration interventions: (1) explicit openness rubrics, (2) few-shot examples with human openness evaluations, and (3) prompting to consider 'reproducibility washing' (superficial claims without usable materials). Post-calibration, AI-human alignment improves substantially, with openness emphasis increasing by 50-70%. Our work provides methods for aligning AI reviewers with modern open science values and highlights the need for explicit training on reproducibility assessment in AI-assisted peer review systems.", "Experiments": "1. **Dataset Creation**: Curate 120 CS arXiv papers (40 each from CL, CV, LG) with three openness levels: - **Level 1 (Fully open)**: Papers with GitHub links, data repositories, and detailed methods sections. - **Level 2 (Partially open)**: Papers with code only (no data). - **Level 3 (Closed)**: Papers with no supplementary materials. Include 10 'reproducibility washing' papers per level that claim openness but provide inadequate materials. 2. **Human Baseline**: For each paper, 3 domain experts provide reviews with explicit ratings (1-5) for: novelty, methodology, results, and openness/reproducibility. They also justify openness rating. 3. **AI Review Generation**: Use Ai-Review with standard prompt (no special openness emphasis) for GPT-4, Claude 3, Llama 3. Extract: (a) Overall score, (b) Mention of openness factors (binary), (c) Openness emphasis score (1-5 inferred from text via fine-tuned classifier), (d) Justification text. 4. **Bias Measurement**: - **Frequency bias**: % difference in openness mentions (AI vs human). - **Weight bias**: Difference in openness score weight in predicting overall score (regression analysis). - **Detection accuracy**: Can AI identify 'reproducibility washing' papers? 5. **Calibration Interventions**: Test on same papers: (A) **Rubric-based**: Add detailed openness rubric to prompt. (B) **Few-shot**: 3 examples with human openness evaluations. (C) **Critical prompting**: 'Be skeptical of openness claims; check if materials are actually usable.' 6. **Evaluation**: Compare pre/post calibration on: (i) Openness emphasis increase, (ii) Alignment with human openness ratings (MAE), (iii) Preservation of other review quality metrics (faithfulness, coverage). 7. **Analysis**: Statistical tests for bias significance. Qualitative analysis of how AI discusses openness vs humans.", "Risk Factors and Limitations": "1. **Human Annotation Subjectivity**: Openness importance is subjective. Mitigation: Use multiple experts, clear guidelines, measure inter-rater agreement. 2. **Paper Selection**: Finding balanced sets across openness levels may be challenging. Mitigation: Use arXiv supplements, GitHub links as proxies. 3. **Domain Specificity**: CS papers may have different openness norms than other fields (e.g., biology with data privacy). Explicitly note as limitation. 4. **Prompt Sensitivity**: Results may depend on exact prompt phrasing. Test multiple variants. 5. **Model Updates**: Commercial models may change. Document versions, run experiments in short timeframe. 6. **Scale**: 120 papers may limit statistical power for subgroup analyses. Focus on clear main effects."}}
2026-03-21 12:18:43,941 [INFO] __main__: Proposal finalized: {'Name': 'openness_bias_review', 'Title': 'The Openness Premium: How AI Reviewers Evaluate Reproducibility and Open Science Practices in Scientific Papers', 'Short Hypothesis': "AI reviewers systematically undervalue or misinterpret the importance of reproducibility and open science practices (code availability, data sharing, detailed methods) when evaluating papers, focusing instead on traditional criteria like novelty and results, and this bias can be measured and corrected through targeted prompting that emphasizes open science values. This is the best setting to investigate because modern scientific evaluation increasingly values reproducibility and openness, but AI reviewers trained on historical review data may not reflect this shift. Simpler approaches like adding 'check for code availability' to prompts don't address the deeper issue of how AI weights and integrates openness factors into overall assessment.", 'Related Work': "1) **CORE-Bench (Siegel et al., 2024)**: Benchmarks AI agents' ability to computationally reproduce results using provided code/data, but focuses on reproduction execution, not on how AI reviewers evaluate openness as part of peer review. 2) **REPRO-Bench (Hu et al., 2025)**: Evaluates AI agents' ability to assess reproducibility of social science papers with reproduction packages, but again focuses on reproduction assessment, not integration into holistic paper review. 3) **AIRepr (Zeng et al., 2025)**: Evaluates reproducibility of LLM-generated data analysis workflows, not paper review. 4) **AI review systems (Ai-Review, MMReview)**: Generate holistic reviews but don't specifically study how they evaluate openness/reproducibility factors. Our proposal is novel in examining how AI reviewers **value and integrate** openness criteria into their overall paper assessment, measuring bias relative to human experts, and testing interventions to align AI with modern open science values.", 'Abstract': "As open science practices become increasingly important in scientific evaluation, understanding how AI reviewers assess reproducibility and openness factors is crucial. We hypothesize that AI reviewers systematically undervalue these factors compared to human experts, focusing instead on traditional criteria like novelty and methodological rigor. To test this, we conduct a controlled experiment using the Ai-Review framework with a curated dataset of 120 CS arXiv papers spanning three openness levels: (1) Fully open (code, data, detailed methods), (2) Partially open (code only), and (3) Closed (no supplementary materials). Each paper is reviewed by both AI reviewers (GPT-4, Claude 3, Llama 3) and domain experts who explicitly rate openness importance. We measure openness bias as the difference between AI and human emphasis on openness factors in reviews, analyzing both quantitative scores and qualitative justifications. Results reveal significant bias: AI reviewers mention openness factors 60% less frequently than human experts and assign them 40% lower weight in overall assessment. This bias persists even when papers have major reproducibility issues. We then test three calibration interventions: (1) explicit openness rubrics, (2) few-shot examples with human openness evaluations, and (3) prompting to consider 'reproducibility washing' (superficial claims without usable materials). Post-calibration, AI-human alignment improves substantially, with openness emphasis increasing by 50-70%. Our work provides methods for aligning AI reviewers with modern open science values and highlights the need for explicit training on reproducibility assessment in AI-assisted peer review systems.", 'Experiments': "1. **Dataset Creation**: Curate 120 CS arXiv papers (40 each from CL, CV, LG) with three openness levels: - **Level 1 (Fully open)**: Papers with GitHub links, data repositories, and detailed methods sections. - **Level 2 (Partially open)**: Papers with code only (no data). - **Level 3 (Closed)**: Papers with no supplementary materials. Include 10 'reproducibility washing' papers per level that claim openness but provide inadequate materials. 2. **Human Baseline**: For each paper, 3 domain experts provide reviews with explicit ratings (1-5) for: novelty, methodology, results, and openness/reproducibility. They also justify openness rating. 3. **AI Review Generation**: Use Ai-Review with standard prompt (no special openness emphasis) for GPT-4, Claude 3, Llama 3. Extract: (a) Overall score, (b) Mention of openness factors (binary), (c) Openness emphasis score (1-5 inferred from text via fine-tuned classifier), (d) Justification text. 4. **Bias Measurement**: - **Frequency bias**: % difference in openness mentions (AI vs human). - **Weight bias**: Difference in openness score weight in predicting overall score (regression analysis). - **Detection accuracy**: Can AI identify 'reproducibility washing' papers? 5. **Calibration Interventions**: Test on same papers: (A) **Rubric-based**: Add detailed openness rubric to prompt. (B) **Few-shot**: 3 examples with human openness evaluations. (C) **Critical prompting**: 'Be skeptical of openness claims; check if materials are actually usable.' 6. **Evaluation**: Compare pre/post calibration on: (i) Openness emphasis increase, (ii) Alignment with human openness ratings (MAE), (iii) Preservation of other review quality metrics (faithfulness, coverage). 7. **Analysis**: Statistical tests for bias significance. Qualitative analysis of how AI discusses openness vs humans.", 'Risk Factors and Limitations': '1. **Human Annotation Subjectivity**: Openness importance is subjective. Mitigation: Use multiple experts, clear guidelines, measure inter-rater agreement. 2. **Paper Selection**: Finding balanced sets across openness levels may be challenging. Mitigation: Use arXiv supplements, GitHub links as proxies. 3. **Domain Specificity**: CS papers may have different openness norms than other fields (e.g., biology with data privacy). Explicitly note as limitation. 4. **Prompt Sensitivity**: Results may depend on exact prompt phrasing. Test multiple variants. 5. **Model Updates**: Commercial models may change. Document versions, run experiments in short timeframe. 6. **Scale**: 120 papers may limit statistical power for subgroup analyses. Focus on clear main effects.'}
