2026-03-21 12:19:40,479 [INFO] __main__: Arguments: {"idea": {"Name": "trick_paper_benchmark", "Title": "TrickPaperBench: Evaluating AI Reviewers on Detecting Methodological Flaws in Scientific Papers", "Short Hypothesis": "AI reviewers can detect subtle, realistic methodological flaws (statistical errors, logical fallacies, missing controls) in scientific papers more accurately than human reviewers, but this capability varies by flaw type and is sensitive to how flaws are presented. This is the best setting to investigate because methodological rigor is a core aspect of peer review, and existing benchmarks don't specifically test this critical reasoning skill. Simpler approaches like evaluating overall review quality don't isolate flaw detection capability.", "Related Work": "1) **ContraReview (previous proposal)**: Tests contradiction detection but not methodological flaws. 2) **ReviewBench (previous proposal)**: Tests robustness to perturbations but not specific methodological errors. 3) **MMReview (Gao et al., 2025)**: Comprehensive benchmark but doesn't include papers with controlled methodological flaws. 4) **CORE-Bench (Siegel et al., 2024)**: Tests AI agents' ability to reproduce results, not to detect flaws in paper methodology. 5) **Statistical error detection in NLP**: Some work on detecting statistical errors in text, but not integrated into full paper review. Our proposal is novel in creating a benchmark specifically for evaluating AI reviewers' ability to detect realistic methodological flaws in scientific papers, with controlled flaw insertion and comparison to human performance.", "Abstract": "Methodological rigor is fundamental to scientific quality, yet many papers contain subtle flaws that slip through peer review. As AI systems are increasingly used to assist review, understanding their ability to detect methodological issues becomes crucial. We introduce TrickPaperBench, a benchmark to evaluate AI reviewers on detecting realistic methodological flaws in scientific papers. We curate a dataset of 100 CS arXiv papers and create modified versions with controlled, subtle flaws: statistical errors (p-hacking, multiple comparison issues), logical fallacies (circular reasoning, false causality), and methodological omissions (missing controls, inadequate baselines). Each paper has both original and flawed versions. We evaluate state-of-the-art LLMs (GPT-4, Claude 3, Llama 3) using the Ai-Review framework, prompting them to review papers and flag methodological issues. We compare AI performance to human domain experts on the same task. Results show that AI reviewers detect certain flaw types (statistical errors) with higher accuracy than humans (75% vs 60%) but struggle with logical fallacies (45% vs 55%). Performance is sensitive to how flaws are presented: explicitly stated flaws are detected more easily than implicitly embedded ones. TrickPaperBench provides a targeted testbed for improving AI reviewers' methodological critique capabilities and reveals both strengths and limitations compared to human reviewers.", "Experiments": "1. **Dataset Creation**: Select 100 CS arXiv papers (CL, CV, LG). For each paper, create 3 flawed versions by introducing one controlled flaw each: (a) **Statistical error**: e.g., p-hacking (selectively reporting significant results), multiple comparison without correction. (b) **Logical fallacy**: e.g., circular reasoning, false causality (correlation presented as causation). (c) **Methodological omission**: e.g., missing control experiment, inadequate baseline comparison. Keep original versions as controls. Validate flaws with domain experts for realism. 2. **Evaluation Protocol**: Use Ai-Review prompt template augmented with: 'Please review this paper with special attention to methodological rigor. Flag any statistical issues, logical fallacies, or methodological omissions.' For each model (GPT-4, Claude 3, Llama 3) and human expert (30 CS researchers), generate reviews for all paper versions. 3. **Metrics**: (i) **Flaw Detection Accuracy**: Binary classification of whether each specific flaw is detected. (ii) **False Positive Rate**: On original (non-flawed) papers. (iii) **Detection Confidence**: Certainty expressions in review. (iv) **Human-AI Comparison**: Accuracy difference between AI and human reviewers. (v) **Flaw Type Analysis**: Performance breakdown by flaw category. 4. **Analysis**: Statistical tests comparing AI vs human accuracy. Qualitative analysis of detection failures (why certain flaws are missed). Ablation: Test with/without explicit instruction to focus on methodology. 5. **Intervention**: Test if providing methodological checklists improves detection.", "Risk Factors and Limitations": "1. **Flaw Realism**: Artificially inserted flaws may differ from naturally occurring ones. Mitigation: Use patterns observed in real paper reviews, validate with experts. 2. **Expert Annotation Cost**: Recruiting human experts for 100 papers is expensive. Mitigation: Use graduate students with training, focus on subset for expert validation. 3. **Domain Specificity**: Limited to CS papers; methodological norms differ in other fields. Explicitly note as limitation. 4. **Prompt Sensitivity**: Detection may depend heavily on prompt phrasing. Test multiple prompts and report best/worst. 5. **Scale**: 100 papers may limit statistical power for some flaw types. Mitigation: Focus on clear effects, use multiple flaws per category. 6. **Evaluation Complexity**: Determining 'detection' from free-text reviews requires careful coding. Use multiple coders, measure agreement."}}
