versions. 3. **Metrics**: (i) **Flaw Detection Accuracy**: Binary classification of whether each specific flaw is detected. (ii) **False Positive Rate**: On original (non-flawed) papers. (iii) **Detection Confidence**: Certainty expressions in review. (iv) **Human-AI Comparison**: Accuracy difference between AI and human reviewers. (v) **Flaw Type Analysis**: Performance breakdown by flaw category. 4. **Analysis**: Statistical tests comparing AI vs human accuracy. Qualitative analysis of detection failures (why certain flaws are missed). Ablation: Test with/without explicit instruction to focus on methodology. 5. **Intervention**: Test if providing methodological checklists improves detection.", 'Risk Factors and Limitations': "1. **Flaw Realism**: Artificially inserted flaws may differ from naturally occurring ones. Mitigation: Use patterns observed in real paper reviews, validate with experts. 2. **Expert Annotation Cost**: Recruiting human experts for 100 papers is expensive. Mitigation: Use graduate students with training, focus on subset for expert validation. 3. **Domain Specificity**: Limited to CS papers; methodological norms differ in other fields. Explicitly note as limitation. 4. **Prompt Sensitivity**: Detection may depend heavily on prompt phrasing. Test multiple prompts and report best/worst. 5. **Scale**: 100 papers may limit statistical power for some flaw types. Mitigation: Focus on clear effects, use multiple flaws per category. 6. **Evaluation Complexity**: Determining 'detection' from free-text reviews requires careful coding. Use multiple coders, measure agreement."}
